The Prague Stock Exchange ended with fewer points at the end of the day
After the rapid fall of the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected its losses.
The transactions of <0xC4><0x8C>EZ shares reached about half the value they have on a normal day.
The Prague Stock Exchange, at the beginning of trading Tuesday, reacted immediately to Monday's fall when it fell to about 6%.
The decline this time is due to the fall in stocks on Wall Street.
Here, too, is the reaction of the market to the result of the vote of the American Assembly of Representatives that refused to support the financial sector secretary's stabilization plan.
Stocks falling in Asia
Asian stocks saw a dramatic drop on Tuesday, though over the course of the day the index finally eased some of the losses.
The Hong Kong Hang Seng Stock Exchange index throughout its financial day scored nearly four percent, although it later mitigated its losses by reducing the decline by nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index following Chinese stock movements on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange fell 3.8 percent, while markets in Shanghai were closed.
Shares of the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent but, in the end, losses fell to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan Stock Exchange, according to the index secretary, fell to 3.6 percent.
“The bailouts planned in the U.S. are insecure and this affects the financial market around the world,” said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Mint.
Although Hong Kong is a part of China, it only determines its monetary policy, i.e. without dependence on the Central Bank of China.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
U.S. lawmakers should meet again as soon as possible, Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd said, and approve a proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, it threatens that falls will be felt in other countries.
Bloody bath of American stocks
On Monday, the American Assembly of Representatives rejected the plan to help the financial system to which $700 billion should be devoted (nearly 12 trillion kronor).
Legislators, in that way, ignored President George Bush’s invitation to support his plan.
For Bush, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
On Monday, U.S. stocks experienced a bloody slump and mostly the stock index picked up the biggest drop in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index dropped to nearly seven percent. A similar volume drop was last recorded in 1987.
The index dropped before it was announced but as soon as it was shown that the assembly proposal was not moving forward, the index began to fall freely.
Congress Withdraws: U.S. Government May Inject $700 Billion into Banking
The highest representatives of Congress and the government, President George W. Bush, agreed on a pact in broad terms of financial assistance to the American financial system.
The vote will take place early next week.
U.S. lawmakers sparked a gap in talks on approving the bailout plan in its form to help the U.S. financial system with the amount of $700 billion (approximately 12 trillion crowns).
However, it is not yet won.
Congressmen must fine-tune some details of the contract before they can make public the final form of the law and before it is voted on.
The financial system aid plan will be discussed Monday at the Assembly of Representatives.
Barney Frank, chairman of the Assembly’s Committee on Financial Services and Banking, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to some sources, the vote on the plan could take place in the Senate no later than Wednesday.
According to economists, the arrival of the ratification of the bailout plan should represent the announcement of a first psychologically significant factor for the revitalization of the financial market.
Afterwards, however, "disenchantment" will be achieved thanks to the complex mechanisms whose market support will also reach in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made a big breakthrough.
We have resolved our disagreements regarding the shape of the package of measures to stabilize the market,” Democrat Nancy Pelosia told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could still be held on Sunday.
Representatives of lawmakers met Sunday night with finance minister Henry Paulson to give a definitive shape to the government Fund.
This should buy from financial corporations unsold mortgage assets that lead financial corporations to severe losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
“We are about to close the agreement on the plan, which will work and should also be effective in the market.
It is still necessary to continue with the sanitation plan, but I think we are already in it," Paulson said.
A Sign for Asian Business
The global financial crisis is explicitly affecting the rapidly declining stock market.
According to Democratic Senator for Nevada, Harry Reid, lawmakers are doing everything in their power to get Congress to definitively approve a deal on Sunday.
They want to reassure investors’ business in the face of the Asian finance market as these are the ones in the first time zone and where Congress could influence Monday’s trade.
However, for now, there is nothing clear with certainty about when the two chambers of Congress will vote and even if they will not stagnate at the last moment with any problem.
Legislators believe it will be passed in the coming days.
The law, however, will undergo a number of changes.
The total amount intended to help the system should be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion must be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush called for.
However, Congress can block the release of the remaining amount if it had the impression that the program does not fulfill its function, which would be another $100 billion and later the last $350 billion.
Bush appreciated the progress of the meetings
On the other hand, the president may veto this decision but Congress may surpass his veto by a majority of votes.
Despite these changes, the basic idea of the program was to gain financial resources for the repurchase of bad mortgage securities whose value fell because hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to finish paying off their mortgages.
“We’ve worked everything.
The Assembly of Representatives would have to be prepared to vote on the law on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
President Bush is also pleased with the progress of the meetings.
Its spokesman, Tony Fratto, announced that Bush is pleased with Saturday's move and that he appreciates "the efforts of both sides to stabilize our financial market and protect our economy."
Limitation of armored contract
The chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, Christopher Dodd, the head of the negotiators, said lawmakers decided on the responsibility of the money from the program to protect taxpayers from their losses, a relieving closure of the planned finance plan.
The new law should also limit so-called armored contracts for directors of the participating companies of the program, and create a committee that will have control of the Fund.
This would have to be directed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We’ve worked very hard on it, and we’ve made great strides toward the agreement that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also includes helping homeowners who have problems with their payments.
The government would have to agree on the new mortgage payments it buys in order to lower the monthly charges of debtors’ installment payments and enable them to stay with their homes.
Marek: psychological help
The proposed plan is, according to Patria Finance’s chief economist, David Marek, a good idea that will be realized but rather difficult.
“And that’s why you don’t know with what mechanism and at what price the problem assets will be bought.
This will be decisive for the sharing of the losses between the financial sector and the government,” Marek said this week, to the iHNed.cz server.
Whether the plan is approved now or early next week is not, according to Marek, so relevant.
“Much more importantly, this week the congressmen will agree on their support and give them their approval as soon as possible.
This important and psychological agreement to reach that approval is, at the moment, the most important thing," Marek insisted.
Armed hand fight: the MP3 player against the mobile.
We advise you how to choose
While almost all mobile plays MP3 files, no MP3 player gets to make calls.
