The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It's probably not going to be long before it arrives.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it on mobil.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is among the most expensive in the whole Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of roaming rate regulation it will probably come to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS sending from abroad will be cheaper than if they send them from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lack of competition that really wants to fight.
Probably this seems paradoxical, since we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to regret that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), said that there is no longer room for any other operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with his own network he no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be quite difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a significant price drop to which also the classic operators had to react.
At the same time, even before sharks like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, similar voices were heard both here and there.
It has been proven that there is room for this type of operators and that they can succeed.
Otherwise, there is no need to look too far for examples.
In February of this year we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
Only after half a year, this operator managed to attract more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
On the other hand, behind Mobilking is the group Penta which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to concentrate on many more specific target groups.
In addition, for them to be able to operate effectively, they have far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not involve relatively large costs in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world, these types of virtual operators typically profile themselves at low costs - they offer cheap calls and SMS messages that, however, often counteract the tighter service offering.
Thus, for example, Tesco mobile in Great Britain offers SMS at least half cheap compared to the competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, the bet on a nothing trivial goal group can also be a good blow.
This operator is specifically aimed at the man.
“The right man chooses Mobilking – he’s the operator he likes and who can be trusted,” says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which works with this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say if similar concept like that of Poland could hook in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epický said: “The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of the service offering it is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be some virtual operator in the Czech Republic that will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic it doesn’t seem too hopeful.
Rather, it’s about the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region,” Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, said in a telephone conversation for mobile.cz.
He indirectly assured that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything possible to avoid any potential competition.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step further to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, so that we can offer our customers not only fixed telephone services but also mobile phone services.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have repeatedly met with all the Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have managed to move forward in the meetings,” said the group’s spokesman, Pavel Kaidl.
Then maybe better times are flashing.
It seems that, for unofficial information, the first official operator would likely have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment we believe that the situation is ideal for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has addressed us with any complex and serious project in this field," said Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>, spokesman for Telefónica O2.
The specificity of the Czech market refers to other operators.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional conformity with O2's opinion, adds: "To date we have not registered any viable commercial projects that, bilaterally profitable, can continue to develop."
“In the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find any virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this moment we should already have on the table some concrete contract that would be possible to study in such a short horizon."
Vodafone focuses its attention on meeting the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this with regard to the allocation of expenses and infrastructure.
We consider it to be the biggest contribution from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this field is to partner with which to establish a shared network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible offices - with nail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a fall in prices and thus a fall in profits.
So why make it easier to enter the competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull the same rope, proof of this is the grip when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the greatest pressure on <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was at the time of the entry of U:fon by the company T-Mobile.
This is attested by the public information available on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> websites.
But precisely now U:fon serves as an argument for why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds: "In addition, not long ago the competitive environment in the mobile phone market was opened to a fourth operator.
As far as the character of the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is concerned, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would mean great demands for him and, above all, for his services.
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously daunting due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
It is not just the position of the <0xC4><0x8C>TU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in trade tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tenders (UOHS).
However, it expressed its typical position on this problem.
The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile phone market would be possible after an agreement was concluded on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator.
To date no agreement has been concluded since the offer of potential stakeholders was rather not interesting enough for classic operators," added Kristian Chalupa, of the Department of External Relations of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For offices that must represent the interests of consumers it is more than a consideration, besides they should note that no one takes advantage of their position in the market.
Especially when Kristian Chalupa adds: "Overseas where virtual operators operate normally we can see that their entry into the market contributed to the lower prices of mobile telephony services"
Obviously, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market media and the fall in prices are not in the interest of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Really how dramatically shocking this whole case is in the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether this is really a coincidence, is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline at the gas stations because it is clear that it is the work of coincidence and a hard fight for competition.
"The Office has found no signs of unfair competition in this regard and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position, therefore, do not have a corresponding rise in responsibility in their actions in the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile phone market to virtual operators are lacking, as are telecom regulators,” Chalupa added.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many conflicting points.
There is obviously an analysis of relevant markets drawn up by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> according to which telecommunications are, from the point of view of the commercial tender, a single market.
In this type of market, of course, none of the Czech traders has a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer another vision - for a virtual operator to emerge it is always necessary to agree with the network administrator.
And the mobile operator - with all its logic - has the monopoly of its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument were not accepted, at least for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS should represent a warning the fact that three mobile operators are moving up strikingly similarly.
The current complaints of the interested parties (included by the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with the operators they collide with many similar impediments.
Carrying responsibility on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS washes its hands in all this matter.
We have met him already in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the Telecommunications Act to extend the competence of <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in the field of commercial tenders was recently introduced, which was not implemented, even when a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
This should be well known to the representatives of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS, but it is evident that their interests are elsewhere.
Everything's fine, when no one looks
At the same time, it unnoticedly continues to function something like a pseudo-virtual operator that already exists in the Czech mobile networks.
They are companies that put their own prices on mobile services which, however, only a part are public.
These are usually companies that are engaged in multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile services.
Usually only a few chosen ones get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the carrier, acts as a classic business customer of the same ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions at all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If cases such as those cited were discovered, there could be talk of a breach of the contractual conditions that could result in the end of the collaboration with the given company," Martina Kemrová replied to the question about this problem.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity carried out by mobile operators would not reach responsible people.
In the case of the three companies mentioned above, they can be thousands of customers.
None of the operators is against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they make not negligible profits and at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epický warns us of possible problems: "the law allows such speculation, however, the services of this company are used only by a negligible as much percent of customers.
These, moreover, must accept that your phone’s SIM card is not in your name so they cannot absolutely dispose of it as a normal carrier customer.”
This is precisely what should seem to the minimally strange <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>.
There is also a new question for the UOHS.
If mobile operators are blind in this type of procedure, why are they blocking the entry of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has sufficient competence to discover these types of activities and if it does not want to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this history and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive
As was already clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a significant decrease in prices of services.
At the same time, in virtually every country where the virtual operator arose, the classic operators tried more or less to protect themselves from this intrusion.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical - too small, a market, eventually too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, at the moment the regulatory bodies have intervened and in no case have they defended the operators but their customers.
Whether with formal measures or informal pressure they managed to emerge the first virtual operator and with it began to emerge others.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Authority passes this whole case as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience we cannot help but be impressed that the confusion of powers in these cases suits them.
But let's not despair.
If this behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator actually gets to these lands, then the Czech mobile market is likely to start moving again.
If any of the operators allow a virtual mobile operator to enter, it will be difficult for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling it more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
