The MHD Prague takes us on Wednesday for the first time with the chip
On Wednesday, 1 October 2008, the history of the Prague Transport Company writes the date when the first passengers enter the metro, tram and bus with an electronic voucher in their pockets instead of a paper ticket.
This can now be purchased by nearly 100,000 people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase the voucher for 30 days, 90 days and the annual voucher (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and simultaneously charge it to their chip card at the transport company's infocenters and stalls at the Metro stations, Muzeum, M<0xC5><0xAF>stek, Nádra<0xC5><0xBE>í Hole<0xC5><0xA1>ovice, And<0xC4><0x9B>l, Rozty<0xC4><0x8D>, Let<0xC5><0x88>
The bonds can be purchased as early as yesterday on the internet on the pages of the transport company, www.dpp.cz.
The service, until the afternoon, was used by more than four hundred people.
Those who start using the internet as a form of commerce can definitely start forgetting the ticket stands at subway stations, where until now they had to regularly queue to get a regular ticket.
The voucher is purchased online, and the Opencard card is recharged at one of the thirteen subsidiaries of the Municipal Library.
"At these locations there is a ready-made staff window at the passengers' disposal that helps interested parties with online purchases and also with the reloading of the purchased voucher on their card," said project spokesman Martin Opatrný.
