Eatonville, the first city entirely inhabited by blacks incorporated into the country and the place of childhood of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet fields, 300 men of color, 300 good swimmers, many guavas, two schools and not one prison."
