Speaking asleep
Some kids talk at night.
I’m not talking about those who wake up very smart and tell us something that happened the day before, but about children who talk while they’re asleep.
The first time it happens you may be scared, but it doesn’t really matter.
It is a benign sleep disturbance called somniloquia.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure more than one has been told he spoke at night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in life for example associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the next day the child remembers nothing.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, nocturnal enuresis (sleeping) or sleepwalking, but it doesn’t have to be so.
As we have already mentioned above, they can also be associated with very high fever, stressful situations or overexcitement.
It is an understudied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
You may speak in a quiet tone of voice, loose words, a murmur or the opposite (screams, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense it would be advisable to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check if there is any question that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives him exit in this way.
We have said that it is a benign disorder, so you have no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stressful picture).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid shows or TV series that are scary or a little violent.
With very nervous children who have a hard time relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain some inner calm.
This will help the child have a quieter sleep.
Once the sleepiness appears, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not conscious, and you will break his sleep.
Even if he's talking, he's asleep and he's resting.
Remember that if you are very distressed during several episodes it would be advisable to consult or find out what is causing so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which isn’t the usual thing), don’t fall into the temptation to make an interrogation to get information from him.
You will get nothing, because when you are asleep you are not conscious to organize your thoughts.
In addition, you will hear what it says, but you do not know what it is dreaming to say that, so very careful in how you interpret the information and with the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him at night to find out his secrets.
Not even joking.
That generates a lot of anxiety.
In short, don’t worry, it’s not bad, it’s an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
