The interview - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has once again become one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And above all, it regained the trust of the public who had been seriously hesitated by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood stores administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Faced with this drama and public discontent, the Government of Canada conducted a public survey in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which sought to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to formulate recommendations to prevent such a disaster from reproducing.
While Judge Krever was slow to present his relationship, certain provinces then set up a committee that aimed to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mission.
As a result of the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, nearly 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
After having made many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work over the years that followed, we have regained the public’s trust,” he says, before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary recalled, however, that " trust is an extremely fragile thing " .
Since its inception on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, we were witnessing in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says Décary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
Then we rely on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we do not know and when a serious disease can emanate from that, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we put in place exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it has been proven beyond all doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense.”
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique for HIV detection appeared on the market: nucleidic acid tests that allow the detection of the presence of the virus and not of antibodies to the virus directly in the blood of donors, on which the tests used so far were based.
Nucleid acid tests allowed to shorten the period between the time the person has been infected and the time the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
We were able to reduce this period by less than a week.
We thus substantially reduce the risk that certain donors will be infected without knowing it and that we will not be able to detect them.
These improvements significantly lowered the risk of getting AIDS from a blood transfusion.
Today, one person in 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
“That means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of transmission of HIV by a blood product occurs.
I believe that you can now receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health without any worries,” says the chief of management of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
It is never known which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant ", Dr. Décary pursues before stressing that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for a sufficient supply.
“Needs increase as the population ages.
Since anti-cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which on average brings together only 3 per cent of Quebecers eligible for blood donation. "
All persons with good health, 18 years of age and who meet the eligibility criteria can however donate blood every 56 days, that is six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who propose their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they traveled to a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
" With this 3%, we managed to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
The hardships are very rare.
But members of this network of donors need to be renewed as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to be a regular donor.
Since today’s life is very rampant, we rarely find the time to spend an hour to donate her blood,” says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for major burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was formerly considered biomedical waste is filled with a rich blood of stem cells that can be used for the treatment of serious diseases such as leukemia.
"We celebrated a few weeks ago, putting in the bank our thousandth sample of blood from the umbilical cord and it is expected to take more than a thousand of these per year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts early next year,” says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood taking program as very popular.
" Many mothers are disappointed not to be able to enjoy this " , since Héma-Québec does not have the resources to propose this complex and costly program at all hospitals in Quebec.
