If Barrick Gold had really wanted a public debate, it is in front of public opinion that he would have had to present his view of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in several of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually about changing ideas rather than sticking.
It was therefore sufficient for the miner to open her books, her files and establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the financing of independent search teams that could have clarified the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and rejects petitions and letters of support for the authors of Noir Canada.
Could Mr. Garver possibly explain how he could ask for a "public" debate despising the views of the latter?
According to the vice president, this word seems to refer only to highly paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; that represents a very limited view of the concept.
In a democracy, detractors also have the right to speak.
What he doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – Barrick Gold, is that the audience that supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada does so mostly because it rejects the miner’s brutal manner.
This audience is willing to listen to Barrick and judge him, but based on civilized changes in arguments, and not within what many people perceive as a persecution-bite (in pursuit of the " public debate " , Barrick Gold has just filed a requirement with respect to the authors of Noir Canada urging them to stop using this word).
