“Everything has been done to cover up the economy and ordinary Americans in the face of the current Wall Street crisis,” she said.
“It’s the fundamental point: if we don’t do this, the trauma, chaos and disturbances about Americans’ daily lives will be immense,” said Republican Judd Gregg.
Negotiations had ended very quickly in the last few hours because they feared the effect that would cause a further failure in investor mood.
The last hour they had set was the opening of the markets this morning.
The two candidates in the U.S. presidential election, who have joined late in the negotiations, were rather supportive of the deal, not forgetting yet to express their discontent about being forced to reach this extremity.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama was given certain provisions to reach the deal, particularly the one that would allow homeowners to keep their homes and the one on the salary of the leaders of the surviving companies by the state.
