Psychology of Overlaps: Why Do We Spend More Money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at New York University discovered the neurological - economic basis for this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study in the journal Science, people don’t want to lose in competitions like eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an overpriced price.
The scientists attempted to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played lottery, the other participated in an auction, and in the meantime, the active areas of the brains of the participants in the experiment were examined using the functional magnetic resonance imaging system (fMRI).
In both games participants could win money, but during the auctions, where it is fundamental to bet more than the other, losing the game intensified the functioning of the complex called stratum located under the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system.
Thus, according to scientists, the increase in betting is explained as a prevention not to provoke an intense reaction of the stratum.
To substantiate their theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment, three groups bet against a person in different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the actual value of the product in question, and its members bet.
Another group was also promised that if they won, they would receive an additional $15 prize.
Instead, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in the event of losing the auction the members of the group lost even that money.
Thus the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, by checking the hypothesis of the neurologists, the members of the group who played "against failure" were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the "winner" group.
“These results cannot be deduced from any previous economic theory.
For those up until now explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should you go to the doctor?
Around 500 million people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the leading causes of death.
The number of people infected in this country is estimated at 100,000, but only 7,000 are treated because many of the sick do not know that they are infected.
The name of hepatitis is the common name for different liver diseases caused by viruses.
The symptoms are very similar; liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogens and the diseases caused are very different.
Hepatitis viruses dependent on the pathogen are spread by two main forms: Hepatitis A and E by diet (for example with water or infected food), Hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body moods (sperm, vaginal humor, saliva).
It is advisable for travelers to protect themselves by vaccine against virus A and B, there are no vaccines against C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two or three weeks after consuming the infected food, manifested by poor general condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that, jaundice appears on the skin and on the white of the eyes, excrement becomes clear, dark colored urine and healing can last even two - three weeks.
Every year, one million people worldwide die from cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to estimates, only one in ten infected people receive pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can produce liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most people do not know that they are ill because this pathological agent gradually destroys liver cells and often the first symptoms appear only 20-30 years later.
Therefore, premature recognition, systematic medical monitoring, is very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and those who wear tattoos.
Currently, there are about 200 million people in the world who suffer from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with a routine laboratory control as well, it is worthwhile to consult with the family doctor when experiencing any unknown symptoms.
The disease has a cure if it is discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so it can suppress the contagion and prevent cancer.
30 September is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their premature recognition.
Does it hurt less for those who believe in God?
According to recent research, religious faith has a calming effect that also relieved the death of the martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed that religious belief in how it influences human pain - reported the British newspaper Telegraph.
In the context of this unique experiment they applied electric shock to 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists, while all were looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the technique of scanning the human brain, it was possible to verify that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
This experiment is the first in a series of researches in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the different departments of the University participate alongside academics.
The analysis occurred as follows; they fixed a sparkling instrument to the patient's left hand, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look at two paintings; the Virgin Mary, a 17th-century work of Sassoferrato and the Lady of the Armi<0xC3><0xB1>o of Leonardo da Vinci of the 15th century.
The researchers hoped that the spectacle of the Virgin Mary would provoke a certain religious mood among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo’s oil because it was not too different from the other, and thought it had a reassuring effect.
Patients spent half an hour on an MRI scanner, receiving in that period 20 electric shocks in four successive parts while observing the religious-themed painting or the other.
The Catholics claimed that when looking at the Virgin Mary they felt in "security" as "protected" people, "they reassured themselves and in their hearts reigned peace."
When they looked at the religious theme picture, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo’s work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image so shocking you can achieve a similar effect with atheists too, you just have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person they feel very positively about, like a mother or a father," the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright celebrated the result of the investigation.
“The exercise of faith should and in many cases really change our personality,” Wright added.
