On its tenth birthday, Google can say: it can be found both in people’s pockets and in the sky above their heads; it knows where they spent their holidays, which doctors they visit and what they are interested in.
But according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company’s executives, this is still not enough.
On the other hand, skeptics who parallel the Orwelian vision do not see the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google’s main goal is to gather as much personal data as possible about its users, and this is necessary to meet the original goals of Google’s founders: “We gather all the information in the world in one system!”
According to the Google leader, the company, even after ten years of work that revolted the World, is still in the early stages of the effort to be able to process all the information.
To the question what is going to happen in five years, Schmidt answered: I would like Google to be able to answer questions such as "What to do tomorrow?" or "What would be the job that best suits me?" - however, software will not be able to answer seemingly simple questions until there is enough information from users.
Not all Internet users are aware that the search keywords, IP addresses and pages they visited at the end of the search are accurately stored during their browsing on the Net.
Thanks to Personalized Search, for example, which debuted two years ago, users can store their own browsing history, they can revisit what they were looking for before, what they opened and thanks to this history will generate much more personalized searches - on this same logic will be based the Recommendations, on which the system will offer us products and services based on the preferences previously defined and stored.
What will happen if they use my data against me, if they collect information about my activities? - ask those users who care about seeing the information monopoly of Google.
In most cases rather the potential represented by the company is what can be fearful and not remorse, fear of punishment, longing for freedom or rebellion against power.
However, it is a fact already confirmed that they not only retain, but in justifiable cases also transfer to third parties all the sought expressions, in these cases there is nothing that protects the personal rights of internet users.
Perhaps the most debated example in recent times was the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, when Google handed over to the Brazilian government the information on its website, called Orkut, to identify pedophiles.
On the other hand, Internet users who care about people’s rights, in May, were relieved when the company together with the EFF, the organization for the defense of electronic rights, successfully demonstrated before the court that it was right in its litigation with the FBI: according to the judgment, Google cannot be forced, through any of the points of the constitution, to provide any kind of information requested in secret.
(At the same time, the federal government managed to get around fifty thousand web addresses and about a thousand search phrases, but without obtaining the search lists of individual users, nor the complete lists of websites and keywords for the last two months.)
So the opinion about Google is quite contradictory: those who are afraid to provide their personal data criticize it because they think their privacy is damaged by starting to use Google’s services, and they rebel against it as against conservative multinational companies.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its enthusiastic followers, internet users and users from other countries, see in them the future generation, the "avant-garde corporation", not so its rival, Microsoft, catalogued by its Windows as conqueror of the World, no matter how much they both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask users for any identification code, nor money for their applications, the code is open and the free program package, constantly updated and seems more youthful, more collaborative than the practice of the official software giant.
But it may also be because geeks accurately see the very problematic relationship between human rights and the Internet that was produced precisely by one of the most mentioned keywords in recent years: the Web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is about collaboration, leaving intentional footprints behind us and taking advantage of the available communication channels, and while the measurements of these vary individually, the essence remains the same: to show ourselves.
A normal young person can have a profile on numerous collective pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and can even link them with other services, such as Twitter or the last.fm that offers a list of their music customs, then these can be included in a tracking system such as the FriendFeed or the Blip.fm, you can also have a blog, in which the most recent photo galleries that are stored in the Flickr automatically appear.
We can know numerous cases from which it follows that for example the bride, seeing the flow of photographs of the next morning from ordinary friends, learns who spent the night before their fraudulent boyfriend or they can fire the employee of a company because he writes his sincere opinion on his blog about the company's address: one thing is certain, the definition of privacy was completely revalued.
A person's "online" life is what she shows of herself - this is the definition that hides behind the behavior of today's youth.
And anyone who wants to hide something, or at least intends to dodge Google’s monopoly, can do so (starting for example with the Scroogle that uses the Google search system, but leaves no traces).
There are many people who don’t want to register on collective pages to prevent them from finding them, but they can replace Google’s “online” apps, from text writing software to image and newsreading apps with alternative versions that don’t connect to gigantic servers or prepare the most perfect profile possible about us.
Public opinion almost openly expects the day when Google shows its true face.
The company with its current value of $156 billion is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion), AdWords/AdSense advertising surfaces threaten the revenues of advertising agencies, while the services that are introduced increasingly quickly cause serious headaches not only to other companies, but also to Microsoft.
Critical observers, however, will find the Chinese contradictions alarming as well: for example, the senior management strongly rejected employee protest after doubling the price of the company’s daycare, they considered the unlimited number of employees’ feeding too expensive, but all this is nothing compared to the fact that in 2006 Google gave in to the pressure of the Chinese government and the company’s entire morality.
One of the company's internal health regulations says that they will not announce any new services in advance, but only when it was ready to operate, which if it is certain that the foreseeable problems of the coming months and years will be able to revolt the world: while some believe that the project of scanning and archiving books and magazines from Google will acquire such dimensions that our company will soon be cited with our health system in the United States, have other problems.
And the fact that Google is going to create a genetic database, will be able to provide a good raw material for the writers of science fiction works, the Scroogled, novel of the popular Cory Doctorow, describes in Orwelian form that future, in which a man only from Google data can be described alarmingly well.
