The smart car mimics the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best method to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of obstacle sensors existing in nature?
For example, the bumblebees.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, bumblebees set the stage for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the nature-imitating BR23C car robotic steering system, which was given the characteristics of bumblebees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can dodge all collisions.
During the flight each bumblebee creates its own particular oval space that actually looks a lot like our protective safety capsule - explained in the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, technological director of PR and development and research.
The composite eyes of bumblebees that are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees play an important role.
To copy the function of the composite eyes, the engineers used the laser-ray length measurement system.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the vehicle’s microprocessor that immediately transforms into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the robot of the vehicle mimicking the movements of the bumblebees, modifying the steering by rotating the wheels to the necessary extent.
Unlike any current system, this maneuver is totally instinctive.
“If it weren’t, the vehicle robot wouldn’t be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Vehicle Robot Project and Mobility Laboratory.
It must react immediately and instinctively, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what a bumblebee does to dodge other bumblebees.
This process should be done in the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bumblebees, the movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for bumblebees to dodge other bumblebees, here they only used as a possibility for the auto robot the rotary movement and acceleration as well as the braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion batteries.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the data processing capacity, let alone the storage capacity.
This device in every second only needs to process a few input signals and react as appropriate.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with instinctive logic based on the data from the previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
No memory of gigabytes or megabytes is needed.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately avoid obstacles, which, according to Nissan’s calculations, will be able to be incorporated into series-produced models within ten years.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, bypassing obstacles in his way.
