The written version of the $700 billion financial bailout package law has been prepared to be applied in several phases to buy bad credits from banks.
In the first phase, half of the money will be spent.
According to East Coast schedules during new consultations that lasted until after midnight on Saturday, congressional leaders reached an agreement on the $700 billion total bailout package, after several days of discussion, Reuters reported.
“We have made significant progress,” said Nancy Pelosi, Democratic president of the U.S. Congress, saying that the deal only needs to be formalized in a document.
The pledge on the package was supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
Henry Paulson, the Minister of Finance, speaking about the outcome of the compromise, said: this program will work and be efficient but more action is needed. According to Pelosi, it is not about saving Wall Street, but about turning the cart of the economy.
The written version of the package was published before the opening of Asian markets, i.e. on Sunday before 8 p.m., according to Washington time (i.e. before 2 p.m. on Monday, according to Central European time), without causing a spectacular jump in the stock market.
On the bill called the 2008 Emergency Economic Stabilization Act, on Monday the first American Congress and then the Senate will vote.
President George W. Bush on Saturday night consulted with Pelosi and then the White House also celebrated the news of the deal.
“We are pleased with the progress made overnight and highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy,” said White House spokesman Tony Fratto.
The program is different from the Bush administration’s original proposal to spend all $700 billion to buy bad-quality credit fund securities.
Now only half of the $700 billion can be spent, using $250 billion immediately after Congress votes, probably on Monday, the Ministry of Finance will buy credit fund securities, of poor rating and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the president's decision.
This program will be monitored by a special body, in which the President of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The other half of the $700 billion can be spent after a new Congressional decision.
According to the law the Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic: you can simultaneously buy bad credits, mortgages and securities of credit fund securities, in addition to other "poisonous" type credits as well.
The purchase can be made at auctions or directly - informed competent people of the ministry.
The law allows affected companies to participate in an insurance program where the finance portfolio guarantees the elements of concern, for which the companies will pay the amount corresponding to the foreseeable damages.
Henry Paulson said that the law ensures the necessary financial means, which can even reach $700 billion to meet the urgent needs of the U.S. financial system, whether it involves buying bad financial means, insuring them or preventing risks that could lead to the collapse of some major financial institutions.
“We do everything we need to be ready to introduce the law as soon as they sign it,” he added.
On the other hand, the heads of the banks who are in trouble and are waiting for the help of the state will be able to count on the official limitation of their indemnities, which the American slang simply calls parachutes of gold.
Only in certain cases will payments be limited, and the limitations depend on the form of assistance provided by the Ministry of Finance.
The limitation means that if the ministry purchases under an auction, an extra tax will be imposed on gold parachutes, unless the bank’s failed head retires.
By buying bad credits directly, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that the compensations of the bosses are not exaggerated.
In addition to the above, existing gold parachute contracts will not be changed, the limitations refer only to new contracts to stimulate participation in the program as well.
This is the first case in U.S. history that a legal limitation on the revenues of CEOs will be in effect, said Democrat Barney Frank, chairman of the congressional commission responsible for financial services.
The State will also have the right to acquire shares of the banks participating in the program, thus reducing the risk of taxpayers, since they will ultimately be able to make profits from the transaction as soon as the economy is recovered and with it the bank.
According to the bill in the next five years, the president will have to present to Congress a proposal on how to return to taxpayers the losses of the financial sector.
Of course, there were those on both sides who expressed their reservations about the project.
“This is not what the American citizens have entrusted us to, that is, they are not protecting taxpayer dollars,” said California Republican Congressman Darrell Issa.
Her Democratic colleague from Ohio, Mary Kaptur, said the measures were urged by those responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices rose 0.1 percent compared to last month's prices and 12.9 percent compared to August 2007's prices - reported the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH).
Industrial export prices rose 1.1 percent from July 2008 and decreased 3.9 percent from the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 percent from the previous month and by 3.2 percent from the previous year.
Industrial sales prices increased only to a minimal extent, at 0.1 percent.
Domestic sales prices for the processing industry sectors rose minimally, at 0.1 percent over the month of July.
The largest increase in the magnitude of prices occurred in August 2008, in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 percent), primarily due to a 4.6 percent monthly increase in bags and belts and a 2.5 percent increase in footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the price of the chemical material production branch (1.6 percent).
There was a price decrease in the petrochemical sector (1.4 percent), in the production of electrical machines and instruments (0.9 percent), as well as - to a minimum extent - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 percent).
The prices of papermaking, publishing and printing did not change.
In the other sectors of the processing industry there was an increase in prices between 0.2 and 0.9 percent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water, which represent an important weight within domestic trade, there was an increase of 0.3 percent in the month of August, first as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from July 1.
In a comparison over a twelve-month period - in domestic sales of the processing industry sectors - the largest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 percent).
In the metal processing sector, there was an increase of 13.2 percent, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industry, of decisive weight, there was an increase of 11 percent.
There was a decrease in prices in the textile industry (2.5 percent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machines and instruments (0.3 percent).
In the rest of the processing sectors the pace of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Over the past year, prices in the global processing industry increased by 10.2 percent.
Electricity, gas, heat and water prices surpassed the previous year’s prices by 18.7 percent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the largest monthly price increase ( 0.7 percent) was recorded in the sectors of investment goods.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 percent, while prices in the energy sector and the intermediate sectors were unchanged from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediate industry (16.8 percent).
In the consumer goods sectors there was a decrease of 6.8 percent and in investment goods a decrease of 1.4 percent.
Industry export prices calculated in HUF increased 1.1 percent from the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 percent.
The price of our national currency in one month fell by 1.7 percent relative to the euro and by 7.1 percent relative to the dollar, compared to August 2007 it strengthened by 7.5 percent relative to the euro and 15.9 percent relative to the dollar.
