Járóka: We must break the vicious circle of poverty and segregation
Today the European Summit for Equal Opportunities has begun in Paris, its host is France which this year is also president of the European Union.
Lívia Járóka, Member of the European People’s Party for Fidesz, in her message addressed to the plenary, as one of the main speakers of this professional meeting, drew attention to segregation in education, because it is one of the most serious violations that plague Roma children and it is also the biggest obstacle to the prevailing foundation of their interests.
This high-level conference was opened - on behalf of the French Presidency - by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs and by Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner responsible for Jobs, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
The meeting was attended by representatives of governments, European social partners and representatives of the most important European organisations for the protection of social rights.
Járóka - according to the press office of the Fidesz group of deputies in the European Parliament - warned that in addition to discrimination in employment, Roma are left out of the labour market in the first place because of their low level of education.
"Most young Gypsies have not completed secondary education and due to the poor quality of basic education, only a small part can obtain a university diploma."
Járóka also stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, has a decisive role in the prevalence of other human rights as well.
Investing in the education of Roma children at an early age can strengthen the economy of the Member States of the European Union.
According to the MEP, it is necessary to raise awareness of these issues both among Gypsies and among non-Gypsies.
For the earlier a gypsy student begins school, the more likely he will be to become an active member of the labor market; through income and consumption taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
"Gypsies, as citizens of the European Union, must be guaranteed the right to quality education and the abolition of segregated and low-level education" - stressed Livia Járóka.
According to the MEP, the objective and active unity of the European Union is necessary to speed up immediately the processes of school desegregation, for which it is of fundamental importance to comply properly with the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, we must offer Roma children the possibility that guarantees the democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as citizens of full rights" - demanded Járóka.
The aim of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities organized annually since last year’s Berlin meeting, which was held in the sign of the “European Year of Equal Opportunities”, is to ensure a unique forum to promote the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at European and national levels of the Member States.
CSU: grace for a transitional period
A decision will be made at the end of October on the fate of the failed duo Huber-Beckstein
Despite the grave electoral defeat, no heads have yet been cut at the top of the Bavarian CSU, for the moment the debate on personal issues has been postponed.
Erwin Huber, party chairman, and Günther Beckstein, provincial prime minister, are still in their posts, but it is not known how long the grace will last.
The fate of the duo, which suffered a catastrophic 17 percent electoral defeat, will be decided at the extraordinary congress of the party that will be held on the last weekend of October.
The members of the much criticized duo gave a glimpse: don’t cling so much to their posts.
