Mp3 readers under accusation, endanger hearing
Listening to high-volume music for a long time using portable music devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent hearing injuries.
The European Commission cites the opinion of the European Union’s Scientific Committee on Emerging and Newly Identified Health Risks (Csserri) published today in a press release published in Bruxel.
“From this scientific opinion, it emerges that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable music devices weekly for more than an hour a day having the device at high volume risk a permanent loss of hearing ability.”
“I’m concerned that such a high number of young people who frequently use portable music and cell phones at elevated acoustic levels can unconsciously ruin their ears in an irremediable way,” Kuneva said.
“From the scientific evidence, a clear risk emerges and we must react quickly.
What counts is to raise awareness among consumers and make this information public.
We must also re-examine existing control systems in the light of this scientific opinion so that they are broadly effective and keep pace with the new technology."
Bruxel had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, seeing the widespread use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise that this causes.
“Scientists confirm that it is a cause for concern and the European Commission will now examine together with member states and stakeholders what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable music and related devices.”
Currently, there is already a European safety standard limiting the noise level of portable music devices to 100 dB, but concern increases as hearing damage can result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to greatly limit these damages by resorting to solutions such as reducing levels and the time of exposure to noise.
In its opinion, the Scientific Committee Ue notes that users of portable music devices listen to music at a high volume (more than 89 decibels) for only 5 hours a week exceed the current limit on maximum noise in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk a permanent loss of hearing ability after a period of 5 years.
It means that it affects 5-10% of the users of such devices and the number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
